U.N. Security Council Meets on Iraq 's Letter
UNITED NATIONS , November 14 ( Xinhua ) -- The United Nations Security Council on Saturday night reviewed a letter from Iraq that promised to resume full cooperation with U.N. arms inspectors .
Iraq 's Deputy Prime Minister sent a letter to U.N. chief Kofi Annan , promising to allow U.N. arms inspectors to return immediately to Baghdad and resume their regular work .
The Council 's review was focused on an annex to the letter , in which Iraq stated its views on the proposed comprehensive review of its compliance with U.N relevant resolutions by the Security Council and the restructure of the United Nations Special Commission ( UNSCOM ) in charge of dismantling Iraq 's weapons of mass destruction .
Among the 15 members of Security Council , the United States was the only one that called Iraq 's offer unacceptable .
The U.S. said Iraq set conditions for its resumption of cooperation in the annex .
Russia said Iraq , both in Baghdad and in New York , had mad it clear that the annex was not listing conditions but stating Baghdad 's view .
China and France shared the same view with Russia .
Britain said it was skeptical about Iraq 's decision .
U.N. chief Kofi Annan confirmed that Iraq 's decision was positive and a step in the right direction .
